<div class="max-w-2xl">
  <div class="flex gap-4">
    <button id="short-btn">
      <span class="text-span text-dark-grey">Short</span>
      <span class="underline-span block h-0.5 w-full bg-primary"></span>
    </button>
    <button id="medium-btn">
      <span class="text-span text-dark-grey">Medium</span>
      <span class="underline-span block h-0.5 w-full bg-primary"></span>
    </button>
    <button id="long-btn">
      <span class="text-span text-dark-grey">Long</span>
      <span class="underline-span block h-0.5 w-full bg-primary"></span>
    </button>
  </div>

  <div id="about-content" class="mt-4">
    <p>
      I'm an Army veteran and UX Engineer who specializes in designing clean,
      minimalist interfaces in Figma and implementing them with modern tools
      like Astro, Next.js, and headless CMSs. My dual background allows me to
      guide projects from concept to completion, ensuring every detail is
      considered. I'm seeking a role at an innovative agency where I can apply
      these end-to-end skills. Outside of work, I'm dedicated to family and
      friends, and you can also find me playing drums, producing, or DJing
      underground electronic music.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
  const paragraphs: string[] = [
    `I’m a UX Engineer with six years of experience bridging the gap between what users need and what technology can deliver. My journey began in development, but I quickly gravitated to the visual and emotional side of the web—CSS opened a door, and soon I was immersed in UX design, Figma, and the art of creating seamless experiences. Today, that hybrid path defines my work: I start every project by talking to users, using the double‑diamond process to define the real problem. I analyze qualitative data with AI, sketch by hand, move through greyscale wireframes, and craft high‑fidelity designs—then I build them with modern tools like Astro, Next.js, and headless CMSs. It’s a full‑circle approach that ensures nothing is lost in translation.`,
    `My Army veteran background is woven into everything I do. It taught me integrity, leadership, and the importance of completing the mission—not just doing the work, but doing it to the best of my ability. That discipline translates directly to my design philosophy: I believe great user experiences are as simple as possible, removing every unnecessary step. I’m a minimalist by nature, whether I’m designing a clean interface or writing concise, maintainable code. I want to bring this end‑to‑end capability to a custom web agency that values modern technology over legacy platforms—somewhere I can contribute both design and development, and collaborate with a team that shares my passion for craftsmanship.`,
    `Outside the digital realm, music is my second language. I produce and DJ drum & bass, play drums, guitar, and piano, and I hold a degree from Berklee College of Music. That background in audio engineering and performance infuses my work with a sense of rhythm, composition, and attention to detail—whether I’m structuring a user flow or layering animations. When I’m not coding or designing, you’ll find me in the studio working up beats, or spinning live on one of the online radio stations I DJ for. I’d love to connect with a team that appreciates the overlap between creative disciplines—and if you’re a fellow musician, we’ll have plenty to talk about.`,
  ]

  const aboutContent = document.getElementById('about-content')

  const buttons: { id: string; paragraphs: number }[] = [
    { id: 'short-btn', paragraphs: 1 },
    { id: 'medium-btn', paragraphs: 2 },
    { id: 'long-btn', paragraphs: 3 },
  ]

  const buttonElements = buttons
    .map(({ id }) => document.getElementById(id) as HTMLButtonElement | null)
    .filter((btn): btn is HTMLButtonElement => btn !== null)

  const updateContent = (numOfParagraphs: number) => {
    if (aboutContent) {
      aboutContent.innerHTML = paragraphs
        .slice(0, numOfParagraphs)
        .map((p) => `<p class='mb-4 leading-relaxed text-justify'>${p}</p>`)
        .join('')
    }
  }

  const setActiveButton = (activeButton: HTMLButtonElement) => {
    buttonElements.forEach((button) => {
      const textSpan = button.querySelector('.text-span')
      const underlineSpan = button.querySelector('.underline-span')

      if (textSpan && underlineSpan) {
        if (button === activeButton) {
          textSpan.classList.add('font-bold')
          underlineSpan.classList.remove('hidden')
        } else {
          textSpan.classList.remove('font-bold')
          underlineSpan.classList.add('hidden')
        }
      }
    })
  }

  buttonElements.forEach((button, index) => {
    button.addEventListener('click', () => {
      const { paragraphs } = buttons[index]
      updateContent(paragraphs)
      setActiveButton(button)
    })
  })

  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    const initialButton = buttonElements[0]

    if (initialButton) {
      updateContent(1)
      setActiveButton(initialButton)
    }
  })
</script>
